    <stitle>VT 275 Engine Diagnostics Manual - Engine Symptoms Diagnostics - Test Procedures - Smoke</stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s305010402.15" svcproctype="diagnose" graphiccount="0">
        <title>Smoke</title>
        <svcsubproc id="s305010402.15.1">
            <title>Black Smoke</title>
            <table id="t305010414" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>Causes</title>
                <tgroup cols="1" align="left">
                    <colspec colname="col1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Air intake or exhaust restriction</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Failed turbocharger or a turbocharger wheel stuck</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Biased Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) sensor</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Loose injector</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Charge Air Cooler (CAC) system leakage</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Altitude (black smoke on hard acceleration or snap acceleration may be pronounced
                                    at higher elevations)
                                </para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Biased Mass Air Flow (MAF) sensor</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Manifold Absolute Pressure (MAP) sensor failed</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>EGR valve stuck open in warm ambient temperature</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>
                <title>Black Smoke Diagnostics</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If engine has fuel knock or there is evidence of fuel in the exhaust, remove exhaust
                    manifolds and inspect for fuel in the exhaust ports. Suspect a loose injector, missing or damaged
                    O-ring and gasket on bottom of an injector.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect air inlet system and exhaust system for possible sources of restriction.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect turbocharger for oil leakage or failure. Some oil carryover is expected
                    due to the closed crankcase ventilation system.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_98.xml" xrefid="tp305010601">Test 1. Diagnostic Trouble Codes</hotlnk>
                    " on the Performance Diagnostics Form or in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_103.xml" xrefid="tp305010606">Test 6. Intake and Exhaust Restriction
                    </hotlnk>
                    " on the Performance Diagnostics Form or in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_108.xml" xrefid="tp305010611">Test 11. Air Management</hotlnk>
                    " on the Performance Diagnostics Form or in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="s305010402.15.2">
            <title>White Smoke</title>
            <table id="t305010415" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>Causes</title>
                <tgroup cols="1" align="left">
                    <colspec colname="col1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Cold engine</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>No glow plug operation</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>No inlet air heater operation</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Aerated oil</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Poor quality fuel</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>EGR stuck open on startup in colder ambient temperatures</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Biased Barometric Absolute Pressure (BAP) sensor</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Coolant leak to combustion from exhaust side</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Loose fuel injectors</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Inoperative fuel injectors</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Bent connecting rods</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Worn piston rings</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Low compression</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Coolant leaking into combustion chamber</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Intake manifold porosity</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>
                <title>White Smoke Diagnostics</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">In cold ambient temperatures, some white smoke is possible depending on conditions.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Ensure that engine is up to operating temperature 88 &#176;C (190 &#176;F) prior to
                            verifying a white smoke complaint.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>If the engine is unable to obtain operating temperature during a road test, verify
                            thermostat opening temperature 88 &#176;C (190 &#176;F).
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">On a cold engine, the glow plugs and the inlet air heater may remain on after the engine
                    starts to assist in cold smoke cleanup. Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_93.xml" xrefid="tp305010514">Tests 14. Glow Plug System</hotlnk>
                    " and "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_94.xml" xrefid="tp305010515">Test 15. Inlet Air Heater System</hotlnk>
                    " in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050105.xml" xrefid="e3050105">Hard Start and No Start Diagnostics
                    </hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual or on the Hard Start and No Start Diagnostics Form to verify glow plug and
                    inlet air heater operation.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_102.xml" xrefid="tp305010605">Test 5. Fuel Supply System</hotlnk>
                    " in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual or on the Performance Diagnostics Form. Verify quality and quantity of the
                    fuel, aeration, and fuel pressure.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do Output State Test Low and High to cycle the EGR valve and monitor valve movement with
                    the Output State Test Continuous Monitor Session.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If there is coolant loss without engine overheating, check for coolant in exhaust.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>If coolant is leaking from exhaust or can be smelled in the exhaust, see "
                            <hotlnk document="eges3052_68.xml" xrefid="s305010402.5.1.1">Coolant Leak to Exhaust"
                            </hotlnk>
                            in this section.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_105.xml" xrefid="tp305010608">Test 8. Injection Control Pressure</hotlnk>
                    " in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual or on the Performance Diagnostics Form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_106.xml" xrefid="tp305010609">Test 9. Injector Disable</hotlnk>
                    " in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual or on the Performance Diagnostics Form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_107.xml" xrefid="tp305010610">Test 10. Relative Compression</hotlnk>
                    " in the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual or on the Performance Diagnostics Form.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If engine has fuel knock or evidence of fuel in exhaust, remove exhaust manifolds and
                    inspect for fuel in the exhaust ports. (Suspect loose injectors, missing or damaged O-ring and
                    copper gasket on bottom of injector).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect air induction system for evidence of water ingestion or evidence of unfiltered
                    air entering the engine.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Water ingestion could have caused a hydraulic lock and bent connecting rods. If water
                            ingestion is suspected, identify smoking cylinders by removing exhaust manifolds and running
                            engine.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Unfiltered air entering the engine can cause excessive power cylinder wear and
                            turbocharger compressor damage. If power cylinder wear is suspected, identify smoking
                            cylinder(s) by removing exhaust manifolds and running engine.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>If coolant is found in the intake manifold, see "
                            <hotlnk document="eges3052_68.xml" xrefid="s305010402.5.1.1">Coolant Leak to Exhaust"
                            </hotlnk>
                            in this section.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid personal injury or death, visually inspect the turbocharger with the engine off, and
                        the turbocharger not spinning. Turbocharger components may be extremely hot and turbocharger
                        wheels are very sharp and may spin at high speeds. Visually assure the turbocharger wheels are
                        not turning before inserting fingers or other body parts.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do compression test on cylinders that are white smoke using the compression test
                    adapter. Inspect turbocharger for damage.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If engine is overheating with coolant loss, and cylinder head gasket, injector sleeve,
                    or glow plug sleeve is suspected for leaking, see "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_65.xml" xrefid="s305010402.2.3.1">Combustion Leaks to Coolant Test using
                        High Pressure
                    </hotlnk>
                    " in this section.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc id="s305010402.15.3">
            <title>Blue Smoke</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Blue smoke is an indication of oil consumption. If unable to differentiate between white and
                        blue smoke, determine smoke type by odor. If there is an odor of oil burning it is blue smoke.
                        If there is a fuel or coolant smell then it is white smoke.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <table id="t305010416" type="simple" frame="topbot">
                <title>Causes</title>
                <tgroup cols="1" align="left">
                    <colspec colname="col1"/>
                    <tbody>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Excessive crankcase pressure</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Failed turbocharger</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Failed fuel injector</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Piston oil control ring stuck or inoperative</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                        <row rowsep="0">
                            <entry>
                                <para>Leaking valve stem seals or worn valve guides</para>
                            </entry>
                        </row>
                    </tbody>
                </tgroup>
            </table>
            <para>
                <title>Blue Smoke Diagnostics</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do oil consumption test on engine. Verify high oil consumption.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Do "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_112.xml" xrefid="tp305010615">Test 15. Crankcase Pressure</hotlnk>
                    " on the Performance Diagnostics Form or the "
                    <hotlnk document="eges3052_E3050106.xml" xrefid="e3050106">Performance Diagnostics</hotlnk>
                    " section of this manual.
                </para>
                <seqlist style="alphalc">
                    <item>
                        <para>If crankcase pressure is high and there is excessive oil consumption, investigate air
                            compressor, turbocharger, and power cylinder components.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>If crankcase pressure is normal and there is excessive oil consumption remove Charge Air
                            Cooler (CAC) pipes and inspect CAC and intake system for excessive oil carryover.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect turbocharger high and low pressure stage shafts for oil leak at both the
                    compressor and turbine housings.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove exhaust manifolds and inspect exhaust ports for oil residue to pinpoint possible
                    injector failure causing oil to mix with fuel injected into the power cylinder.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
